<br>
I feel that I must lead off with admitting first that my perspective is a kind of bastardized mix of realism and idealism.  I'm sure you can tell that already, but I wanted to spell out that I'm aware of it.<br>
<br>
It does sensibly follow that violence begets violence.  That terrorism begets terrorism.  And that war begets war.<br>
<br>
The difference?<br>
<br>
War has an objective.  Is usually about subjugation and domination for a purpose.  That purpose is clearly defined.  Certain lines are drawn.  There is a certain sense to war, in that it scales.  The deployment of violence is greater, so are the terms, so are the objectives.<br>
<br>
Why do we call 9/11 terrorism?  An Al Qaeda person would call it war.  Holy war, in fact.  Jihad is the word.<br>
<br>
Because the act of violence did not strategically lend to the fulfillment of an objective.  Psychologically?  Maybe.  Be inducing fear or terror (or attempting to as the case may be?)  Maybe.<br>
<br>
War campaigns, in the classical traditional sense, are better defined.  Draw the lines.  Advance.  Capture territory.  Redraw the lines.  Advance.  The opponent capitulates or you capture all his territory.  By those same rules, one does not need to eradicate non-strategic targets in the process.  Weapons bunkers?  Yeah.  Factories?  Yeah.  Farms?  No.  <br>
<br>
(Not until Vietnam where the questionable ploy of &quot;starving them into capitulation&quot; came into play.  And as we learned the hard way, it's not a war campaign anymore.  Flirts with terrorism even, I'd say.  Boy did we screw THAT one up.)<br>
<br>
But my point being, the lines are drawn, battalions are mustered and deployed, ordinance is deployed, all in the cohesive strategic purpose of accomplishing a well-defined objective.<br>
<br>
Case in point, THIS is war:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
December 11, 1941<br>
<br>
The President's Message<br>
To the Congress of the United States:<br>
<br>
          On the morning of Dec. 11 the Government of Germany, pursuing its course of world conquest, declared war against the United States. The long-known and the long-expected has thus taken place. The forces endeavoring to enslave the entire world now are moving toward this hemisphere. Never before has there been a greater challenge to life, liberty and civilization. Delay invites great danger. Rapid and united effort by all of the peoples of the world who are determined to remain free will insure a world victory of the forces of justice and of righteousness over the forces of savagery and of barbarism. Italy also has declared war against the United States.<br>
<br>
          I therefore request the Congress to recognize a state of war between the United States and Germany, and between the United States and Italy.<br>
<br>
                                                                                                Franklin D. Roosevelt<br>
<br>
<br>
The War Resolution <br>
          Declaring that a state of war exists between the Government of Germany and the government and the people of the United States and making provision to prosecute the same. <br>
<br>
          Whereas the Government of Germany has formally declared war against the government and the people of the United States of America:<br>
<br>
          Therefore, be it Resolved by the Senate and House of Representatives of the United States of America in Congress assembled, that the state of war between the United States and the Government of Germany which has thus been thrust upon the United States is hereby formally declared; and the President is hereby authorized and directed to employ the entire naval and military forces of the government to carry on war against the Government of Germany; and to bring the conflict to a successful termination, all of the resources of the country are hereby pledged by the Congress of the United States <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Note the tone and the wording.  There is much that it says.  And much that it does not say.  It suspends the Writ of Habeas Corpus.  It effectively declares marshal law.  The armed forces can camp on your farm and eat your winter crop as they move from their stationed base to their port of departure.<br>
<br>
But there is an honour to it.  A commitment undertaken by a nation and all its people to accomplish a certain aim.<br>
<br>
This is not a drive-by shooting.<br>
<br>
This is not an extremist group blowing up their own in a civilian establishment like Sbarro.<br>
<br>
Yes war begets war, but the stakes are so high it demands both the worst of a people in their committed obstinate fury and the best of a people as they must choose to retain their own honour and humanitarianism as they accomplish that objective.<br>
<br>
And when conducted without too much subversion, at the conclusion of war there follows a time of peace.<br>
<br>
Until the next war.<br>
<br>
Yes, sadly.  Until the next war.<br>
<br>
I don't see any evidence of the human race as a people at having evolved beyond war.  The strategic use of violence is the only force that people of all cultures, creeds, nations, and ethnicities understands.  We don't agree on anything else.<br>
<br>
All the rights we have as Americans were purchased in blood.  In 1776.  In 1812.  In 1865.  In World War I.  In World War II.  Korea, Vietnam, and Gulf '90 I'm not so sure; the morality of it is harder for me to grasp.<br>
<br>
Every utopian society in the history of the world secured their peace with war.  And lost it with war.<br>
<br>
Such is the cycle.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying making war on Iraq is right or wrong.  I honestly am not sure.  We should make war for the right reasons, or we should not make it.  And once committed, we must be committed.  Or we shouldn't run our mouths.  That's my belief.<br>
<br>
Theo<br>
